<div class="case-study__body">
  <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md" data-aos="fade-up">
    <h3 class="section-title">Cutting through the noise</h3>
    <p class="p--large">Did you volunteer or make a donation last year? Likelihood is you did at least once. And so do most people – in fact, most wish they did more. Bright Funds helps companies build a culture of volunteering and giving back. Benefits like matching donations and offering volunteer time off is a great way for companies to invest in their people’s interests outside of work. And they’re helping better their community at the same time.</p>
    <p class="p--large">It’s a win win.</p>
    <p>Bright Funds offers a product that companies use to run their giving, matching, and volunteering programs.</p>
    <p>What we were seeing from our data and hearing from the people at companies who run their giving programs was that people love the giving and volunteering benefits we offer, but they were being under used.</p>
    <p>People are busy at work (that’s a good thing!). But as a result, soft benefits like having your donations matched were slipping through the cracks.  An engineer and I took up the challenge to understand why benefits like this weren’t being used and to iterate through possible features that could boost awareness and usage.</p>

    <h3>Early insights</h3>
    <p>To get started, I held conversations with employees, looked at usage data, and read through customer support conversations to understand what motivates people to give and what was holding them from using their giving and volunteer benefits.</p>
    <p>We learned that:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Overall awareness within companies can be low.</strong><br>People are busy with their work and daily lives. Often, giving benefits are explained as part of an employee’s onboarding, but people are already way too overloaded in those first few weeks. Giving and matching doesn’t stick.</li>
      <li><strong>People often only log in once per year.</strong><br>Many companies run a service week or end of year giving campaign where they drum up awareness. After that many people don’t come back. </li>
      <li><strong>People don’t know everything they can do.</strong><br>For example, we get people reaching out with questions like: “I made a donation to a friend’s race, can that be matched?”. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>These problems result in people leaving matching on the table that they could have used or not taking advantage of their volunteer benefits.</p>

    <h3>From problem to opportunity</h3>
    <p>I repositioned the problems we found were holding people back into opportunities.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>How might we make people aware that their company offers great donation and volunteering benefits.</li>
      <li>How might we encourage people to give and volunteer throughout the year (people want to do this anyway!</li>
      <li>How might help people take full advantage of all the giving and volunteering benefits they have.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Next, we began thinking through possible solutions for these opportunities.</p>

    <p>There’s not one magic method to decide on which projects to take on. In this case, we made decisions based on what we believed would have high impact, what would be within our desired effort to build (we wanted to keep each project small, around 2-4 weeks work), and whether we’ve heard specific requests from clients. We chose a range of projects that would target the problems pinpointed.</p>

    <h3>Onboarding</h3>
    <p>Focus: <span class="definition-badge">Understanding features</span></p>
    <p>The first time someone logs in is a critical moment. Our job is to help that person get to the ‘aha’ moment of understanding why this product deserves a spot in their life. Some pieces of the onboarding process were working ok, but we knew we could do better.</p>
    <p>People were most likely to come back if they shared a bit about how they’d like to volunteer and made their first donation. By doing so, we could follow up with that person about volunteer opportunities. They would also experience a peak when seeing that their donation was doubled by their company matching.</p>
    <p>To guide someone through their initial experience, we developed an ‘onboarding checklist’.</p>
    <p>This checklist welcomed the person to the product and walked them through a few simple things they could do. For example, we ask what skills they might be interested in volunteering. Then, if there is a volunteer opportunity with a matching skill we can let that person know. We encourage someone to get started by making their first donation or requesting a match. This checklist helps someone understand what they can do and provides some quick moments of accomplishment.</p>

  </div>

