    <h3>Fundraising</h3>
    <p>Focus: <span class="definition-badge">Awareness</span>, <span class="definition-badge">Frequency of usage</span></p>
    <p>We knew that the awareness of giving and matching programs could be pretty low in companies. Soft benefits like these aren’t critical to someone’s work and they don’t earn the same attention as benefits like insurance and retirement savings.</p>
    <p>We wanted to increase awareness. At the same time, we were wary of a traditional awareness campaign, because each company handled their internal comms differently. Company A might use email, company B Slack, company C an internally built tool. On top of that, each company would likely want to control what they say, how they say it, and when. And we also weren’t sure how effective something like awareness emails would be. We didn’t want to invest effort in a project that would result in messages silently landing in inboxes.</p>
    <p>However, we did know that fundraising is a key driving of giving. Giving someone the power to raise money for a cause - for a birthday, for a race, for a personal reason - is a proven way to pull others in. People give because they were asked by a friend.</p>
    <p>Our hunch was that we could encourage people to fundraise on Bright Funds with the knowledge that donations would be matched (therefore doubling the amount raised). This would be a trojan horse. The coworkers that supported the fundraiser would then be introduced to Bright Funds and could learn about the other benefits available to them.</p>

  </div>

