    <h3>Goal setting</h3>
    <p>Focus: <span class="definition-badge">Frequency of usage</span></p>
    <p>This project was an outlier. It was larger than the other three and required more design and development work. But based on research from other fields (especially retirement saving) we were interested to see whether having someone set a goal for how much they’d like to give would result in them giving more or giving more often. </p>
    <p>The problem we were seeing was that an employee (let’s call her Rachel) gives sporadic one-time donations. She donates when her company runs a giving or volunteer campaign, and then beyond that when she’s asked by friends. At the same time, we heard that people like Rachel thought they should be giving more.</p>
    <p>Our hypothesis was that if Rachel was prompted to make how much she would like to give concrete by setting a goal and then make it easy for her to follow up with her intentions, she would be more likely to give more and more often.</p>
    <p>When Rachel logs in, she can set a goal. First, she selects which percentage of her salary she’d be interested in giving. We provide a benchmark of 6% based on research indicating that is how much people believe others should give.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--engagement" data-aos="fade-up">
      <img src="../images/cs-engagement/goal-01.jpg" class="image-full__img" alt="Product design mockup of search page">
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md" data-aos="fade-up">

    <p>Then she selects her income range. We decided on income ranges rather than exact income to combat privacy concerns people may have.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--engagement" data-aos="fade-up">
      <img src="../images/cs-engagement/goal-02.jpg" class="image-full__img" alt="Product design mockup of search page">
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md" data-aos="fade-up">

    <p>Lastly, she sees a dollar amount for her goal and can make changes if she’d like.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--engagement" data-aos="fade-up">
      <img src="../images/cs-engagement/goal-03.jpg" class="image-full__img" alt="Product design mockup of search page">
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md" data-aos="fade-up">

    <p>To make the next step actionable, we provide a few suggested ways to donate. Knowing that Rachel might be wary of donating on the spot, we also have an option to send a reminder in a month.</p>
    <p>Progress toward the goal was displayed on Rachel’s account whenever she logged in. She also received a few emails throughout the year with feedback about her progress.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--engagement" data-aos="fade-up">
      <img src="../images/cs-engagement/goal-04.png" class="image-full__img image-full--no-shadow" alt="Product design mockup of search page">
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md" data-aos="fade-up">

      <h3>Positive results</h3>
      <p>This series of product updates not only spurred more donations throughout the year, but were also loved by our customers and internal teams. When comparing monthly donations to the previous year, we saw a growth of over 10%. Personalized tips, advice, and goals made our product tailored to each person’s unique reasons for giving. We saw teams within companies running fundraisers through Bright Funds ranging from annual yoga festivals, pride month, and Relay for Life. And the onboarding checklist provided a framework that the team could tweak to better guide users through the product.</p>

      <p>There was also much more to do. We purposefully limited the size of each project to around two weeks. That meant keeping a close eye on what was in scope. Especially with tips and goal setting, there was a lot we could do to provide the best personalized advice. Understanding what someone cares about, how they view giving, and what their life is like all can help us serve up unique suggestions on how they could give. However, we made the decision at the start to get work out the door and iterate further later. This projects provided the basis for the team to grow and experiment with.</p>

